<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-625-339  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 625 339.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 16 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan: tough new hacker law proposed.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanComputer hackersLegislationInformation Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPAN: TOUGH NEW HACKER LAW PROPOSED 11/16/90 TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 NOV 16 (NB)-- Given the recent spate of computer hackers stealing or destroying computerdata via online networks in Japan, the Japan Information ProcessingDevelopment Association has called for a harsh new penalty for computerhacking -- they would be sentenced up to one year of hard labor, or given ahefty fine.andM;The association seeks the revision of the current criminal law or theenactment of new legislation to more strongly punish hackers who havewillfully destroyed or stolen data by breaking into forbidden areas of acomputer system.andP;  The group claims that the current criminal law isunsuitable for recent developments in computer crime, and that it isnecessary to maintain social faith in the computer information processingsystem.andP;  It also proposed that unlawful acquisition of data, unlawful use ofcomputers, and the destruction of data by means of computer viruses alsoshould be punished as criminal offences.andM;The proposal is based on the results of studies conducted since 1985 by acommittee made up of criminal code scholars, computer maker experts, and banksystem developers.andM;(Ken Takahashi/19901116)</TEXT></DOC>